# Fluff Date: 2026-03-03 21:44:47
<overview>
<p>The Padilla Heavy Artillery Tank entered Star League Defense Force service in 2620 as a deliberate complement to the lighter Chaparral Missile Artillery Tank. Where the Chaparral prioritized speed and terrain exploitation, the Padilla offered a heavier, better-protected platform capable of sustaining fire operations under more demanding tactical conditions. Designed and produced by Leopard Armor of Terra, the seventy-five-ton tracked vehicle carried a single Arrow IV launcher as its primary armament, backed by pulse lasers and an anti-missile system for self-defense. The Padilla's combination of exceptional speed for its weight and robust armor made it one of the most survivable artillery vehicles of the Star League era, and the design proved so effective that few variants were ever deemed necessary. The near-total destruction of Padilla stocks during the Succession Wars left the type among the rarest surviving SLDF vehicles in the modern Inner Sphere.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Padilla's combat effectiveness centers on its Katyusha Arrow IV missile launcher, mounted in a sleek forward box configuration that allows it to operate in close terrain without raising a conspicuous launcher profile. The Arrow IV system provides unmatched flexibility in munitions selection, from conventional high-explosive warheads to homing rounds requiring target designation by TAG-equipped allied units, to specialized payloads. Two Martell medium pulse lasers provide short-range defensive firepower with accuracy advantages over conventional laser designs, while a Burrow anti-missile system offers protection against incoming missile attacks. Early service revealed the Burrow susceptible to electronic jamming, prompting the SLDF quartermaster corps to initiate a McArthur anti-missile replacement program, though most Padillas assigned to front-line combat units never received the upgrade before the Amaris war ended production entirely.</p><p>The Ragusson 375 XL Fusion engine provides a cruising speed of fifty-four kilometers per hour and a flank speed of eighty-six, remarkable performance for a seventy-five-ton tracked vehicle. For a long time, speed was the Padilla's most effective defense: only the fastest recon BattleMechs or purpose-built pursuit vehicles could close to effective engagement range against a Padilla choosing to withdraw. The targeting system includes an integrated TAG designator, allowing the Padilla to self-designate targets for its own homing Arrow IV rounds when no dedicated TAG support is available. StarSlab armor provides reasonable protection for the vehicle's weight class, sufficient to withstand the light direct fire likely to reach a properly deployed artillery vehicle.</p><p>The elaborate security protocols that developed around the Padilla's operation ultimately became a tactical liability. Commanders deemed individual vehicles too valuable to risk in aggressive firing positions, and the Padilla became a symbol of prestige, making each one a high-priority target for opposing commanders who recognized the psychological impact of its destruction.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>A Succession Wars modification performed exclusively by House Liao on Padilla hulls stripped of their Arrow IV launchers and target acquisition gear during the resource crises of the early Succession Wars. FarFire LSR-Launcher XXs were installed in place of the original system, allowing the hulls to remain nominally in service as fire support vehicles despite the loss of their Arrow IV precision capability. No documentation exists of this modification being performed by any faction other than the Capellan Confederation, and the conversion is considered rare even within former Liao inventories.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Padilla Heavy Artillery Tank grew directly from the Star League Defense Force's experience operating the Chaparral Missile Artillery Tank in combined-arms formations. While the Chaparral had proven itself a fast and effective Arrow IV platform, field commanders observed that its relatively light construction and lack of cellular ammunition storage equipment limited its operational endurance under sustained enemy fire. Leopard Armor of Terra received a contract in the late 2610s to develop a heavier complementary vehicle capable of holding firing positions the more fragile Chaparral could not maintain. The resulting Padilla entered service in 2620 and immediately took its place alongside the Chaparral in SLDF combined-arms artillery formations.</p><p>In practice, the two vehicles functioned as a team. Chaparrals would advance alongside TAG-equipped BattleMechs to forward firing positions, delivering precision homing strikes before repositioning to avoid counter-battery fire. Padillas maintained sustained indirect fire from better-protected rear positions, their heavier armor and anti-missile defenses allowing them to weather attritional fire that lighter artillery units could not endure. The combination was devastatingly effective, and the Arrow IV triad of Chaparral, Padilla, and TAG-equipped designator became one of the SLDF's most feared combined-arms systems during the Star League's final decades.</p><p>The Amaris Civil War began the destruction of both designs. Fighting on Terra during Operation Liberation devastated Leopard Armor's production facility along with Grumman Industries' Chaparral lines, and the Great Exodus denied the Inner Sphere the technical base needed to maintain what little survived. By the First Succession War, only twenty Padillas remained operational, all in the hands of House Liao. Even those eventually proved impossible to maintain in their original configuration: stripped of their Arrow IV launchers and target acquisition gear, surviving hulls were fitted with FarFire LSR-Launcher systems to remain nominally in service, gutting the design's effectiveness. ComStar subsequently rebuilt and mothballed the Terra facility, preserving the manufacturing capability for decades without activating it.</p><p>When the Word of Blake secured Terra in 3058, they activated the mothballed Leopard Armor facility to produce Padillas for the Word of Blake Militia, the first new-production Padillas since before the Amaris war. This production continued through the early Jihad years until the broader collapse of Blakist military infrastructure ended it. In the post-Jihad period, the Republic of the Sphere inherited Terra and with it the Leopard Armor facility, resuming Padilla production to supply Republican armed forces. The Padilla's extraordinary operational history, from Star League combined-arms doctrine through Succession Wars attrition, Blakist resurrection, and Republican service, reflects both the soundness of Leopard Armor's original design and the enduring relevance of heavy mobile artillery on the Inner Sphere battlefield.</p>
</history>

